reviewText: Why is it that unwatchable garbage like AQUA TEEN HUNGER FORCE enjoyed a decent amount of cult popularity while this vastly superior show gets no love? While it's animation was admittedly not the greatest (a reality of most TV animation that we must face), JOHNNY TEST featured terrific scripts, great voice acting and was genuinely laugh-out-loud funny. There were also a ton of jokes that went right over the heads of the kids in the audience -- the gay leatherboy race of mole-people immediately springs to mind -- and a wildly anarchic sensibility that made this show a breath of fresh air among the seemingly endless wave of POKEMON and its numerous knockoff shows. If you missed it during its initial run, I highly recommend this set. I have not seen all of the third season and nothing at all from season four so I can't really comment on those other than to say that the animation quality deteriorates (which is not good since the animation was already quite limited), but the first two seasons are comedy gold.
summary: The Most Unfairly Underrated Cartoon of the Past Two Decades

reviewText: Meet Johnny Test - not to be confused with another kid with a similar name.  He's just your average 11-year-old boy with a workaholic mom, overly strict dad, scientist sisters, and a talking dog.Okay, that last part kinda makes him less than average, but Johnny is a real go-getter and always up for almost anything as long as it's up to his boyish interests from super powers to a turbo-charged scooter or backpack.  No matter what crazy experiment his sisters Susan and Mary do to him, he along with his dog and canine confidante Dukey somehow get into trouble but then suddenly find a way out of it.  That's how this crazy series works with 26 episodes from the first 2 seasons on 3 discs.  (And P.S., you may want to note that the art and animation style is different when comparing the first and second seasons down to each and every episode.)It's quite a collection, you know.  Plus, there's big bonus features like DVD-ROM content, a sneak peek at the Johnny Test video game, and bonus episodes of other shows like "Super Duper Sumos", "Gadget Boy", and "Potatoes and Dragons".  And make sure you follow the "flaming-headed boy" and his big adventures every day on Cartoon Network.
